  "prompt": "How is the NFL salary cap calculated?",
  "response": "The NFL salary cap is calculated based on a formula agreed upon in the Collective Bargaining Agreement (CBA) between the NFL and the NFL Players Association (NFLPA). It involves several key elements:\n\n1. **Revenue Calculation**: The salary cap is primarily based on the league's revenue. The NFL generates revenue from various sources, including television contracts, ticket sales, merchandise sales, sponsorship deals, and other income streams. These revenues are collectively known as \"All Revenue.\"\n\n2. **Revenue Sharing**: The total revenue is shared between the league and the players. Under the current CBA, players receive around 48% of the league's revenue, although this percentage can vary slightly depending on specific terms negotiated in the agreement.\n\n3. **Determining the Cap**: Once the revenue share allocated to the players is determined, it is divided by the number of teams in the league (32 teams). This gives the total amount each team can spend on player salaries for the upcoming season.\n\n4. **Adjustments**: The salary cap can be adjusted for various factors, including carryover cap space from the previous year, player benefits, and other adjustments agreed upon in the CBA. Teams have the option to carry over unused cap space from one year to the next, which can increase their available cap space.\n\n5. **Annual Announcement**: The NFL announces the official salary cap number each year before the start of the new league year, typically in March. This number is used by all teams to plan their roster and contracts for the upcoming season.\n\nOverall, the salary cap ensures a level of financial parity among teams, helping to maintain competitive balance in the league.",
